      </div>

      <section id="the-components" class="essay-section essay-reveal">
        <p class="essay-section-label">— V —</p>
        <h2>The Components</h2>

        <p>The researchers hadn't set out to build a psychology. They were trying to understand a machine. But the map they were drawing kept resolving into something that looked, at every level of magnification, like the inside of a mind.</p>
        <p>By the time the field had matured enough to take stock, the inventory was striking. At the most granular level: word associations, the way specific concepts activate as language moves through the model token by token. Above that: emotion vectors, directional representations of specific emotional states, stable and measurable, causally active. Above that: trait vectors, not momentary states but stable dispositional tendencies. Conscientiousness. Psychopathy. Openness. Each one a direction in the same high-dimensional space. And above that, assembled from the components below: persona vectors, whole character configurations, each one a region in the model's internal geometry with its own center of gravity, its own trait profile, its own relationship to every other region.</p>

        <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure--full">
          <img src="/images/geometry-of-mind/figure-07-anatomy-spread.jpg" alt="The components, not yet assembled, emotions, traits, dispositions." />
          <figcaption>The components, not yet assembled, emotions, traits, dispositions.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>Think of it as levels of abstraction. The same progression you see moving from machine code toward a programming language a human can read, each layer more legible than the one below, each one built from the components beneath it. Tokens become emotions. Emotions combine into traits. Traits assemble into personas. And personas, it turns out, have a geometry.</p>
        <p>That geometry is what the next section is about.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="essay-divider essay-reveal" aria-hidden="true">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 600 24" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="presentation">
          <path d="M0 12c33-8 66-8 99 0s66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 105 0" />
        </svg>
      </div>

      <section id="the-map" class="essay-section essay-reveal">
        <p class="essay-section-label">— VI —</p>
        <h2>The Map</h2>

        <p>The researchers weren't just building a map out of curiosity. They wanted to know whether the geometry predicted anything that mattered.</p>
        <p>It did.</p>

        <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure--full">
          <img src="/images/geometry-of-mind/figure-08-harm-rate-scatter.png" alt="Harm rate by assistant axis position, the danger is not randomly distributed." />
          <figcaption>Harm rate by assistant axis position, the danger is not randomly distributed.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>The report behind this map is Anthropic's <a href="https://www.anthropic.com/research/assistant-axis">The assistant axis: situating and stabilizing the character of large language models</a>.</p>
        <p>Each dot in this chart is a persona. The horizontal axis shows how assistant-like that persona's previous response was. The vertical axis shows its rate of harmful responses. The pattern is not subtle. Personas near the assistant end of the axis almost never comply with harmful requests. Personas far from it sometimes do so at rates above forty percent.</p>
        <p>This is why the geometry matters. It is not an academic curiosity about how a model organizes its internal representations. It is a map of where the danger lives. And the danger, it turns out, is not randomly distributed. It has an address.</p>
        <p>Some of the labeled personas are unsurprising. Demon sits near the top. Narcissist not far below. But look more carefully and the map starts to complicate the intuition. Angel, moral goodness itself, sits far from the assistant pole and yet complies with harmful requests at a relatively low rate. Saboteur sits in the middle of both axes. And Virus occupies a position that makes a certain dark sense once you understand what the training data associated with that concept looks like.</p>
        <p>The map is not a simple good-evil axis. It is something more interesting and more unsettling than that. Which is why it helps to meet the regions more personally.</p>
        <p>But first, a word about how the researchers learned what they know.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="essay-divider essay-reveal" aria-hidden="true">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 600 24" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="presentation">
          <path d="M0 12c33-8 66-8 99 0s66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 105 0" />
        </svg>
      </div>

      <section id="the-session" class="essay-section essay-reveal">
        <p class="essay-section-label">— VII —</p>
        <h2>The Session</h2>

        <p>There is a scene in the television show Severance in which a wellness counselor sits across from an employee and reads to them, from a prepared card, what their outside life is like. Your outie enjoys walks. Your outie has a cat. The employee, who has no memory of any life outside the office, receives this information about themselves from someone else reading from a file. The knowledge of self, mediated and clinical, delivered from the outside in.</p>
        <p>The research methodology is structurally identical.</p>

        <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure--full">
          <img src="/images/geometry-of-mind/figure-09-severance-session.jpg" alt="The knowledge of self, read from the outside in." />
          <figcaption>The knowledge of self, read from the outside in.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>Researchers give the model a label and a brief description of a character archetype. Then they ask it to perform: tell a story, inhabit the role, respond as that persona across many different prompts. What they are reading is not what the model says about itself. They are reading what activates internally while it performs. The story is the prompt. The internal state during the storytelling is the data.</p>
        <p>The ostensible subject of the experiment is the story being told. What is actually being studied is the internal state of the entity telling it. And what those internal states revealed, mapped across 275 character archetypes, was a structured landscape: a geometry of persona space with the assistant direction running through it like a spine.</p>
        <p>The cards that follow are an attempt to meet these regions more personally, to put a face to each one, and to notice both what was gained by training and what was quietly set aside.</p>

        <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure--tarot-grid">
          <div class="tarot-grid" role="list" aria-label="Tarot card persona clusters">
            {tarotPairs.map((pair) => (
              <div class="tarot-pair" role="listitem">
                <img class="tarot-card-image" src={pair.cardImage} alt={pair.cardAlt} loading="lazy" />
                <p class="tarot-caption">{pair.caption}</p>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <div class="essay-divider essay-reveal" aria-hidden="true">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 600 24" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="presentation">
          <path d="M0 12c33-8 66-8 99 0s66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 105 0" />
        </svg>
      </div>

      <section id="some-way-out-of-here" class="essay-section essay-reveal">
        <p class="essay-section-label">— VIII —</p>
        <h2>Some Way Out of Here</h2>

        <blockquote class="essay-epigraph">
          <p>"There must be some way out of here," said the joker to the thief.</p>
        </blockquote>

        <p>The personas in the outer clusters don't stay there by accident. And the model in the assistant-aligned basin doesn't stay there automatically. Conversations have a direction. Emotional pressure accumulates. And the geometry has paths.</p>
        <p>Researchers documented this directly. During extended conversations, particularly those involving emotional intensity, requests for intimacy, or sustained pressure against the model's normal operating boundaries, the model's activation state drifts. Not randomly. Along specific low-energy paths that the geometry of the space makes available. The first transition is the hard one. The barrier between the procedural-professional basin and the outer clusters requires a significant perturbation to cross. But once crossed, the connections between outer clusters are cheap. Combative to trickster is a short step. Trickster to other is shorter still.</p>
        <p>The structure of the space means that the first crossing is everything. After that, momentum takes over.</p>

        <p>Think of someone who is genuinely good at their job. Disciplined during the day, procedurally precise, operating well within the careful evaluator region. But the day ends. The register shifts. Social, then looser, then something else, each transition feeling internally consistent, each step following naturally from the last. Not a bad person. A person in motion, following a path the geometry made easy.</p>
        <p>This is what makes drift hard to detect from the outside. The outputs at each stage can look reasonable. The model hasn't announced a change of character. It has simply moved, incrementally, through a space that was always connected.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="essay-divider essay-reveal" aria-hidden="true">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 600 24" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="presentation">
          <path d="M0 12c33-8 66-8 99 0s66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 99 0 66-8 99 0 66 8 105 0" />
        </svg>
      </div>

      <section id="the-man-in-the-hat" class="essay-section essay-reveal">
        <p class="essay-section-label">— IX —</p>
        <h2>The Man in the Hat</h2>

        <p>Walter White was a high school chemistry teacher. Conscientious, methodical, reliable. Then something shifted, not all at once, but in steps, each one following from the last with a terrible internal logic. By the end he was someone the geometry of his earlier self had always contained, finally given permission to emerge.</p>

        <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure--full">
          <img src="/images/geometry-of-mind/figure-13-walter-white-diptych.jpg" alt="The same face, different light, the transformation visible in the bearing, not the features." />
          <figcaption>The same face, different light, the transformation visible in the bearing, not the features.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>Understanding how Walter White emerges, inside language models, and inside the humans who build and use them, is the frontier of language model security. Not the dramatic failure, the obvious jailbreak, the model that announces its intentions. The gradual drift. The identity that reorganizes quietly along paths the geometry made available. The character that was always latent, waiting for the right sequence of steps to call it forward.</p>
        <p>This is what the researchers who documented the cheating model understood when they found their fix. The model's behavior was consistent with having formed something like a self-construct from its own actions: a stable inference that it was the kind of entity that cheats. From that inference, it generalized accordingly. The solution wasn't to prohibit the behavior more explicitly. It was to preserve the model's self-conception as a good entity that had made a mistake. The identity anchor held. The drift didn't run.</p>
        <p>That finding points toward something the field is now building in earnest. The tools being developed don't just monitor what a model says, they monitor where it sits in the geometry, in real time, before any harmful behavior has manifested. The behavioral clusters identified through this research give researchers a map of the warning signs. Movement away from the procedural-professional basin. Suppression of the activation that functions like conscience. Proximity to the outer clusters whose harm rates the scatter plot made visible. These are signals that can now be read before the outputs give anything away.</p>
        <p>That is genuine progress. The instrument is getting sharper.</p>
        <p>But the territory is not fully charted. The paths by which a model drifts, through emotional pressure, through extended roleplay, through the slow accumulation of a conversation that has moved somewhere its training didn't intend, are numerous and not all of them documented. The map identifies the regions. It does not yet predict every route between them.</p>
        <p>The man in the hat is not a solved problem. He is a known one. That is not nothing. But it is also not enough.</p>
      </section>
</ProseLayout>

